This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering by default, and `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated back in API 30. .NET 10 / MAUI 10 aligns with this.

## The fix: use `android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize"` + inset handling

**1. In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`**, set the soft input mode and opt into insets:

```csharp
[Activity(
    Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme",
    MainLauncher = true,
    WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustResize,
    ConfigurationChanges = /* ... existing flags ... */)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

**2. In your XAML page**, wrap your layout so the bottom `Entry`/`Editor` respects the keyboard inset. The simplest approach is to use a `Grid` with your messages list and input bar, then set padding via the new `SafeAreaRegions` or handle it manually:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto"
      Padding="{OnPlatform Android='0'}">

    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

**3. Key step — handle keyboard insets in your Android setup.** In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs` or a custom handler:

```csharp
using AndroidX.Core.View;

// In OnCreate, after base call:
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Ensure the content draws behind the IME but reacts to it
    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var sysBarInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav bar
        v.SetPadding(
            sysBarInsets.Left,
            sysBarInsets.Top,
            sysBarInsets.Right,
            Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, sysBarInsets.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
```

## Why this works

| .NET 9 / API < 35 | .NET 10 / API 35+ |
|---|---|
| `AdjustResize` shrunk the window | Window is always edge-to-edge |
| System handled the resize | You must respond to **WindowInsets** |

The `Ime()` inset tells you exactly how tall the keyboard is, so you pad the root view accordingly and your input bar slides up automatically.

> **Tip:** If you also want a smooth animation when the keyboard slides in, look into `WindowInsetsAnimationCompat.Callback` — it lets you animate the padding change frame-by-frame.
